         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translation</head>
            <p>17th, until the 6th hour, 30[. . .]; 18th until ?,  *  ?[. . .];  20th until the 10th hour, 3[. . .]. If anyone of the [. . .], 
            reason a fast [. . .] for each month [. . .]for thousand-named Isis [. . .] Agathos Daimon, priest [. . .]</p><p/></div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>There seems to be reference to periods of time; ω probably for ὥ(ρα ?; star possibly for denarius. 
                    The figures at the beginning of lines 1-2 must represent days of the month and are followed in each case by a formula indicating a period of time; 
                    the symbols thereafter, probably figures, presumably refer to what must or must not be done during that period </p>
            <p> line 1 the time limit expressed in hours is replaced by the sign * between dots which are probably interpuncts. if it means denarius, its usual sense, or Χοῖνιξ 
                    as probably in a graffito at Dura (<bibl><title>Excavations at Dura-Europos</title> II (Yale, 1931) 147</bibl>), 
                    the cutter has perhaps omitted the time limit in error and what prescribed was a sum of money or a measure of corn; but it would be more satisfactory if it 
                    indicated the time-limit. The letters that follow suggest no likely word; 
                    there is no doubt an abbreviation.</p>
            <p> line 4 The word used for a fast is one connected with the Cyrenean cult of Isis by Herodotus, IV.186. 
               For fasts among worshippers of Isis, see Apuleius Metam.XI.23. Ferri, Studi e Materiali di Storia delle Religioni III (1927) 233 ff. argued that there was evidence for local features in the cult objects found in the 
                    Iseum beside the Acropolis. </p>
            <p> line 7 perhaps to be identified with the priest of the same name in <ref type="inscription">131</ref>, line 2, dated in 102 C.E.</p>
            <p><!--  Pugliese Carratelli Miscellanea Rostagni (1963) 162 f, Maia 16 (1964) 108f.--> </p>
         </div>
         
